<DOC><DOCNO> AP880606-0295 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-06-88 1936EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f AM-InvestmentFund     06-06 0176</FIRST><SECOND>AM-Investment Fund,0184</SECOND><HEAD>Trio Launches Investment Partnership</HEAD><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Two top executives of Metromedia Co. and a formerdirector of PaineWebber Group Inc. have joined forces to set up a $1billion investment boutique specializing in leveraged buyouts.   The partnership, to be called Kluge Subotnick Perkowski andamp; Co.,expected to invest in friendly buyouts in a variety of industriesboth in the United States and abroad, according to a statementissued Monday.   The general partners are Metromedia Chairman John W. Kluge,Metromedia Executive Vice President Stuart Subotnick, and John F.Perkowski, a 15-year veteran of PaineWebber, where he served asdirector of the investment banking division.   Subotnick and Kluge will contribute $100 million for initialcapitalization, but the parternship expects to raise another $900million from limited partners.   Metromedia is a privately held partnership with interests intelecommunications, robotic painting and computer software. Thecompany recently acquire Ponderosa Restaurants and a majorityinterest in Orion Pictures.   It previously owned and operated the largest independenttelevision broadcasting company in the nation, among otherbusinesses.</TEXT></DOC>